---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "The Newsroom — South Bay Today";
const dateStr = "Wednesday, April 15, 2026";
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description="Original reporting from the South Bay. Real stories, real sources, no filler."
  themeColor="#FAF9F6"
  fontsUrl="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Playfair+Display:ital,wght@0,400;0,500;0,600;0,700;0,800;0,900;1,400;1,700&family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700&family=Space+Mono:wght@400;700&display=swap"
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <style>
      :root {
        --n-bg: #FAF9F6;
        --n-card: #FFFFFF;
        --n-ink: #1A1A1A;
        --n-muted: #555555;
        --n-light: #888888;
        --n-border: #C8C4BC;
        --n-border-light: #E5E2DB;
        --n-accent: #C0392B;
        --n-accent-light: #FDEEEC;
        --n-serif: 'Playfair Display', Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif;
        --n-sans: 'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system, sans-serif;
        --n-mono: 'Space Mono', monospace;
        --n-max: 960px;
      }
      body {
        font-family: var(--n-sans);
        background: var(--n-bg);
        color: var(--n-ink);
        margin: 0;
        -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
      }

      /* ── Masthead ── */
      .news-masthead {
        max-width: var(--n-max);
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 32px 24px 0;
        text-align: center;
      }
      .news-masthead-rule { height: 3px; background: var(--n-ink); margin-bottom: 12px; }
      .news-masthead-top {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: space-between;
        align-items: center;
        margin-bottom: 6px;
      }
      .news-masthead-date,
      .news-masthead-edition {
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 10px;
        letter-spacing: 0.06em;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        color: var(--n-muted);
      }
      .news-masthead-logo {
        text-decoration: none;
        color: var(--n-ink);
      }
      .news-masthead-title {
        font-family: var(--n-serif);
        font-size: 56px;
        font-weight: 900;
        line-height: 1;
        letter-spacing: -0.02em;
        margin: 0;
      }
      .news-masthead-subtitle {
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 11px;
        letter-spacing: 0.35em;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        color: var(--n-muted);
        margin-top: 4px;
      }
      .news-masthead-rule-thin {
        height: 1px;
        background: var(--n-border);
        margin-top: 14px;
      }
      .news-masthead-rule-double {
        border: none;
        border-top: 3px double var(--n-border);
        margin: 6px 0 0;
      }

      /* ── Home link ── */
      .news-home-link {
        display: inline-flex;
        align-items: center;
        gap: 6px;
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 11px;
        letter-spacing: 0.04em;
        color: var(--n-muted);
        text-decoration: none;
        padding: 10px 0;
        transition: color 0.15s;
      }
      .news-home-link:hover { color: var(--n-ink); }

      /* ── Content ── */
      .news-content {
        max-width: var(--n-max);
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 0 24px 48px;
      }

      /* ── Hero article ── */
      .news-hero {
        padding: 28px 0 24px;
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--n-border);
      }
      .news-hero-category {
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 10px;
        font-weight: 700;
        letter-spacing: 0.12em;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        color: var(--n-accent);
        margin-bottom: 8px;
      }
      .news-hero-headline {
        font-family: var(--n-serif);
        font-size: 42px;
        font-weight: 900;
        line-height: 1.1;
        letter-spacing: -0.02em;
        color: var(--n-ink);
        margin: 0 0 10px;
        max-width: 720px;
      }
      .news-hero-deck {
        font-family: var(--n-serif);
        font-size: 18px;
        font-weight: 400;
        font-style: italic;
        color: var(--n-muted);
        line-height: 1.45;
        margin: 0 0 14px;
        max-width: 640px;
      }
      .news-hero-byline {
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 10px;
        letter-spacing: 0.06em;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        color: var(--n-light);
        margin-bottom: 18px;
      }
      .news-hero-body {
        font-size: 15px;
        line-height: 1.72;
        color: var(--n-ink);
        max-width: 640px;
      }
      .news-hero-body p {
        margin: 0 0 14px;
      }

      /* ── Article grid ── */
      .news-grid {
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
        gap: 0;
        border-top: 1px solid var(--n-border);
      }
      .news-article {
        padding: 24px 0;
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--n-border-light);
      }
      .news-article:nth-child(odd) {
        padding-right: 24px;
        border-right: 1px solid var(--n-border-light);
      }
      .news-article:nth-child(even) {
        padding-left: 24px;
      }
      .news-article-category {
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 9px;
        font-weight: 700;
        letter-spacing: 0.12em;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        color: var(--n-accent);
        margin-bottom: 6px;
      }
      .news-article-headline {
        font-family: var(--n-serif);
        font-size: 22px;
        font-weight: 800;
        line-height: 1.2;
        letter-spacing: -0.01em;
        color: var(--n-ink);
        margin: 0 0 6px;
      }
      .news-article-deck {
        font-family: var(--n-serif);
        font-size: 14px;
        font-style: italic;
        color: var(--n-muted);
        line-height: 1.4;
        margin: 0 0 8px;
      }
      .news-article-byline {
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 9px;
        letter-spacing: 0.06em;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        color: var(--n-light);
        margin-bottom: 12px;
      }
      .news-article-body {
        font-size: 14px;
        line-height: 1.68;
        color: var(--n-ink);
      }
      .news-article-body p {
        margin: 0 0 12px;
      }

      /* ── Source box ── */
      .news-source {
        margin-top: 12px;
        padding-top: 10px;
        border-top: 1px solid var(--n-border-light);
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 10px;
        color: var(--n-light);
        line-height: 1.5;
      }
      .news-source a {
        color: var(--n-muted);
        text-decoration: none;
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--n-border-light);
      }
      .news-source a:hover {
        color: var(--n-ink);
        border-color: var(--n-ink);
      }

      /* ── Footer ── */
      .news-footer {
        max-width: var(--n-max);
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 24px 24px 48px;
        text-align: center;
        border-top: 3px double var(--n-border);
      }
      .news-footer-text {
        font-family: var(--n-mono);
        font-size: 10px;
        letter-spacing: 0.06em;
        color: var(--n-light);
        line-height: 1.7;
      }
      .news-footer-text a {
        color: var(--n-muted);
        text-decoration: none;
      }
      .news-footer-text a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

      /* ── Responsive ── */
      @media (max-width: 700px) {
        .news-masthead { padding: 24px 16px 0; }
        .news-masthead-title { font-size: 36px; }
        .news-content { padding: 0 16px 40px; }
        .news-hero-headline { font-size: 28px; }
        .news-hero-deck { font-size: 16px; }
        .news-hero-body { font-size: 14px; }
        .news-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
        .news-article:nth-child(odd) {
          padding-right: 0;
          border-right: none;
        }
        .news-article:nth-child(even) {
          padding-left: 0;
        }
        .news-article-headline { font-size: 20px; }
        .news-masthead-top { flex-direction: column; gap: 2px; }
      }
    </style>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- ── MASTHEAD ── -->
  <header class="news-masthead">
    <div class="news-masthead-rule"></div>
    <div class="news-masthead-top">
      <span class="news-masthead-date">{dateStr}</span>
      <span class="news-masthead-edition">Vol. 1, No. 1</span>
    </div>
    <a href="/" class="news-masthead-logo">
      <h1 class="news-masthead-title">South Bay Today</h1>
    </a>
    <div class="news-masthead-subtitle">The Newsroom</div>
    <div class="news-masthead-rule-thin"></div>
    <hr class="news-masthead-rule-double" />
    <nav style="text-align: left;">
      <a href="/" class="news-home-link">&larr; Back to southbaytoday.org</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <!-- ── CONTENT ── -->
  <div class="news-content">

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
         HERO: Whole Foods Los Gatos
         Source: Whole Foods Market press release, March 18, 2026
         ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <article class="news-hero">
      <div class="news-hero-category">Business &middot; Los Gatos</div>
      <h2 class="news-hero-headline">Bigger Cart, Same Town: Whole Foods Reopens on Los Gatos Boulevard</h2>
      <p class="news-hero-deck">The grocery chain's 30-year bet on Los Gatos doubles down&mdash;literally&mdash;with a store nearly twice the size of its predecessor and, at long last, a parking lot.</p>
      <div class="news-hero-byline">South Bay Today &middot; April 15, 2026</div>
      <div class="news-hero-body">
        <p>Whole Foods Market opened the doors of its new Los Gatos store at 15650 Los Gatos Blvd. this morning at 9 a.m. At 43,130 square feet, the location nearly doubles the footprint of the previous store a short distance up the boulevard&mdash;which served the town for more than three decades.</p>

        <p>The relocation brings expanded departments, a dedicated coffee and juice bar, additional seating, and something the old store famously lacked: a larger, dedicated parking lot. Regular hours going forward are 8 a.m. to 10 p.m. daily.</p>

        <p>The store is carrying more than 2,000 local items sourced from over 350 California-based suppliers, curated with help from Patrick Wyman, the company's forager for local and emerging brands. Produce from Tomatero Farm in Watsonville and Coke Farm in San Juan Bautista anchors the entrance. The cheese counter features Andante Dairy and Nicasio Valley Cheese; the bakery stocks Acme Bread Company and Firebrand Artisan Breads. The wine department lists 500-plus bottles from 110 local wineries, alongside 330 craft beers from 40 local breweries.</p>

        <p>The first 300 customers received a limited-edition Los Gatos tote bag and a "Secret Saver" coupon worth up to $100. Coffee and pastry samples from local suppliers were also on offer.</p>

        <p>As part of its Nourishing Our Neighborhoods program, Whole Foods is donating an all-electric refrigerated van to West Valley Community Services, the Cupertino-based nonprofit that picks up surplus food from local Whole Foods stores for distribution. Monetary donations are going to Ma'alot Farms and the River of Life Food Pantry.</p>

        <p>The new store sits at the south end of the Los Gatos Boulevard commercial corridor. The company's own web listing for the location uses the URL slug "losgatosalmaden"&mdash;a quiet acknowledgment that the store's catchment extends well beyond the town line, into the Almaden Valley neighborhoods just over the hill in San Jose.</p>

        <p>Three decades into the chain's presence in Los Gatos, the town now has the version of the store the company has been wanting to build.</p>

        <div class="news-source">
          Source: <a href="https://www.wholefoodsmarket.com/company-info/newsroom/news-releases/new-whole-foods-market-in-los-gatos-calif-to-open-april-15" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Whole Foods Market press release</a>, March 18, 2026.
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
         GRID
         ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="news-grid">

      <!-- ── 1. Flock Safety Lawsuit ──
           Source: Institute for Justice press release + case page (ij.org)
           IJ filed the lawsuit — this is THEIR press release about THEIR case -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Civil Liberties &middot; San Jos&eacute;</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">Three Residents Sue San Jos&eacute; Over 474 License Plate Cameras</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">The Institute for Justice files a federal class action challenging the city's Flock Safety surveillance network.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 15, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>Tony Tan, Scott West, and Colin Wolfson filed a federal class action lawsuit today at the Robert F. Peckham Federal Building in San Jos&eacute;, challenging the city's network of 474 Flock Safety automated license plate reader cameras as unconstitutional warrantless surveillance under the Fourth Amendment.</p>

          <p>The suit was filed by the nonprofit Institute for Justice as part of its national campaign against ALPR abuse. According to IJ, San Jos&eacute;'s Flock database was searched nearly 2.5 million times in the last half of 2025&mdash;an average of more than 15,000 searches per day. More than 1,000 SJPD employees and employees of nearly 300 other government entities in California have access to the data.</p>

          <p>The city first entered a pilot program with Flock Safety in 2021, placing four cameras at a single intersection. It has since expanded to 474. IJ attorney Michael Soyfer described the system as one of the largest anywhere, and said the organization's goal is to push these cases up to federal appellate courts and ultimately to the Supreme Court.</p>

          <p>Several local jurisdictions&mdash;including Santa Clara County, Los Altos Hills, and Mountain View&mdash;have already canceled their Flock contracts over abuse concerns, according to IJ.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://ij.org/press-release/three-san-jose-residents-file-federal-class-action-lawsuit-over-citys-mass-surveillance-of-drivers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Institute for Justice press release</a>; <a href="https://ij.org/case/san-jose-license-plate-readers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IJ case page</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 2. SB 79 Housing Law ──
           Source: CA Legislature bill text (leginfo.legislature.ca.gov)
           + VTA station locations (public knowledge) -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Housing &middot; South Bay</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">The State Law About to Reshape Every Light Rail Neighborhood</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">SB 79 takes effect July 1. Here's what's actually in the bill&mdash;and what it means for cities built around VTA stations.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 15, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>Senate Bill 79, authored by Sen. Scott Wiener, was chaptered on October 10, 2025 and takes effect July 1. The law requires cities to allow multifamily housing on any residentially, commercially, or mixed-use-zoned parcel within a half mile of a qualifying transit stop&mdash;regardless of local zoning.</p>

          <p>The bill establishes two tiers. Tier 1 covers heavy rail and high-frequency commuter service; Tier 2 covers light rail and qualifying bus rapid transit. For Tier 2 stops within a quarter mile, minimum building heights are 65 feet. Beyond a quarter mile in cities of 35,000 or more, the minimum is 55 feet. Minimum densities range from 30 dwelling units per acre up to 120 near Tier 1 stops.</p>

          <p>Affordability requirements baked into the law mandate that 7 to 13 percent of units be reserved for lower-income households&mdash;55 years for rentals, 45 years for ownership. Buildings exceeding 85 feet must meet prevailing wage and skilled-workforce requirements.</p>

          <p>In the South Bay, VTA's light rail stations qualify as Tier 2 stops. That puts neighborhoods around stations in Campbell, Sunnyvale, Mountain View, and San Jos&eacute; squarely in the law's crosshairs. Campbell, with three stations and compact geography, is particularly exposed. Cities can adopt alternative plans before July 1 if the state signs off&mdash;but the alternative must preserve the same total housing capacity the law would otherwise require.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billNavClient.xhtml?bill_id=202520260SB79" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SB 79 bill text</a>, California Legislature.
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 3. Measure A Sales Tax ──
           Source: Santa Clara County press releases (news.santaclaracounty.gov) -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Fiscal &middot; Santa Clara County</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">Two Weeks In: What the New Sales Tax Is Paying For</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">Measure A went into effect April 1, adding five-eighths of a cent to every dollar spent in the county. Here's the plan for the $330 million.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 15, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>Santa Clara County's Measure A sales tax&mdash;approved by 57 percent of voters in November 2025&mdash;took effect April 1, raising the county rate from 9.125 to 9.750 percent. The five-eighths-of-a-cent general tax is expected to generate approximately $330 million annually over its five-year life.</p>

          <p>The revenue is aimed squarely at offsetting federal funding cuts to the county's public hospital system and other critical services. The Board of Supervisors has adopted an ordinance establishing a Citizens' Oversight Committee&mdash;a seven-member independent advisory body modeled after the panel that tracks the county's $950 million affordable housing bond from 2016.</p>

          <p>The committee will receive annual financial audits and expenditure reports, and issue a public annual report on how Measure A revenues are spent. An independent external auditor will also report to the committee.</p>

          <p>Two weeks into the tax's life, the dollars are flowing. Whether $330 million a year is enough to plug the federal gap remains an open question&mdash;but the oversight structure, at least, is built to let residents track the answer.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://news.santaclaracounty.gov/board-supervisors-establishes-oversight-committee-2025-measure-sales-tax-funds" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Santa Clara County press release</a> (oversight committee); <a href="https://news.santaclaracounty.gov/board-supervisors-takes-mid-year-budget-action-offset-federal-funding-cuts-impacting-critical" target="_blank" rel="noopener">County press release</a> (budget action).
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 4. Distracted Driving Month ──
           Source: City of San Jose press release (sanjoseca.gov), April 2, 2026 -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Safety &middot; San Jos&eacute;</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">Fourteen Electronic Signs. Five March Fatalities. One Message.</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">San Jos&eacute; is blanketing high-crash corridors with bilingual reminders to put the phone down.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 15, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>San Jos&eacute;'s Transportation Department has placed 14 electronic message signs along high-crash corridors throughout the city for Distracted Driving Awareness Month. The signs display rotating messages in English and Spanish: "Eyes Up Phones Down," "People Crossing," "Slow Down," and "Conduzca Despacio."</p>

          <p>The campaign comes with urgency. San Jos&eacute; had been on a three-year downward trend in traffic fatalities&mdash;from a high of 65 in 2022 to 41 in 2025. But five fatal crashes in March 2026 alone threatened to reverse that progress.</p>

          <p>Supplementing the signs, the San Jos&eacute; Police Department's Traffic Enforcement Unit is conducting targeted distracted driving enforcement operations through the month.</p>

          <p>The signs are not subtle. They do not need to be. Sixty-five people died on San Jos&eacute; streets four years ago, and the five March deaths are a reminder that the improvement is fragile.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://www.sanjoseca.gov/Home/Components/News/News/7239/4699" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City of San Jos&eacute; press release</a>, April 2, 2026.
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 5. #WeCreate408 ──
           Source: City of San Jose Office of Cultural Affairs (sanjoseca.gov) -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Arts &middot; San Jos&eacute;</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">San Jos&eacute;'s Free Creativity Challenge Is Back for Year Eight</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">A daily creative prompt, delivered to your inbox, all month long. You don't need to be an artist.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 15, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>#WeCreate408 is San Jos&eacute;'s month-long online creativity challenge, now in its eighth year. Run by the city's Office of Cultural Affairs, the program sends daily creative prompts to anyone who signs up at wecreate408.org&mdash;along with suggestions for creative activities happening around San Jos&eacute;.</p>

          <p>The challenge is designed for everyone, not just people who consider themselves artists. The city explicitly says so: "You don't need to consider yourself an 'artist' to take part." Participants share their work on social media with the #WeCreate408 hashtag.</p>

          <p>This year's Creative Ambassadors include Los Panaderos (Sharon and Tanya Ben&iacute;tez), Mexican Folk Dancers, and filmmaker and educator Tricia Creason-Valencia. The program is part of San Jos&eacute;'s April Arts, Culture, and Creativity Month.</p>

          <p>It's free. It's low-pressure. And it's a genuinely charming thing for a city government to run.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://www.sanjoseca.gov/your-government/departments-offices/cultural-affairs/participate/we-create-408" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City of San Jos&eacute; Office of Cultural Affairs</a>; <a href="https://www.sanjoseca.gov/your-government/departments-offices/cultural-affairs/participate/creative-ambassadors/2026-creative-ambassadors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">2026 Creative Ambassadors</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 6. Animal Shelter ──
           Source: City of San Jose press release (sanjoseca.gov/Home/Components/News/News/7246/4699)
           Quotes from Torralba and Mahan are from the city's OWN press release -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">City Hall &middot; San Jos&eacute;</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">San Jos&eacute; Is Moving Its Animal Shelter Back Where It Started</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">Animal Care and Services returns to the Parks Department on August 1, two decades after it was originally housed there.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 14, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>San Jos&eacute; has announced that Animal Care and Services will transfer from the Public Works Department to Parks, Recreation and Neighborhood Services on August 1&mdash;returning the shelter to the department where it was originally housed when it opened in 2004.</p>

          <p>City Manager's Office spokesperson Danielle Torralba said the transition reflects the administration's goal of optimizing the city's service delivery. Mayor Matt Mahan said the move will help strengthen community-based services and improve outcomes for animals.</p>

          <p>The reorganization places the animal shelter under the same umbrella as Happy Hollow Park and Zoo and Emma Prusch Farm Park, consolidating the city's animal-related programs.</p>

          <p>The move follows a 2024 city audit that cited overcrowding, unsanitary conditions, inadequate medical care, and poor record-keeping at the shelter. Whether a different org chart fixes those problems is an open question&mdash;but it puts animal services alongside the city's other animal programs for the first time in years.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://www.sanjoseca.gov/Home/Components/News/News/7246/4699" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City of San Jos&eacute; press release</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 7. West Valley Housing Resource Fair ──
           Source: Town of Los Gatos news flash (losgatosca.gov) -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Community &middot; Los Gatos</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">Los Gatos Co-Hosts a Housing Resource Fair Today</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">The West Valley cities are pooling resources to help residents navigate one of the most expensive housing markets in the country.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 15, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>The West Valley Housing Resource Fair is happening today, April 15, co-hosted by the Town of Los Gatos. The event connects residents with housing assistance programs, information on below-market-rate units, and resources from the West Valley cities collaborative&mdash;which includes Los Gatos, Campbell, and Saratoga.</p>

          <p>The timing is notable. SB 79 takes effect July 1 and could dramatically reshape housing density around transit stops across the South Bay. Measure A's $330 million in annual revenue is partly aimed at protecting the county hospital system that serves residents who can't afford private care. And the median home price in Los Gatos remains north of $2 million.</p>

          <p>Against that backdrop, a resource fair isn't going to solve the South Bay's housing crisis. But it's a concrete step by three small cities toward helping the residents who are already here.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://www.losgatosca.gov/m/newsflash" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Town of Los Gatos news flash</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 8. Hack Cupertino ──
           Source: City of Cupertino event page (cupertino.gov) -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Community &middot; Cupertino</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">Cupertino's Annual Teen Hackathon Wrapped This Weekend</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">Hack Cupertino has been sending teenagers into a community center with laptops and caffeine since 2017. This year's theme: health and wellness.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 14, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>Hack Cupertino 2026 ran overnight from April 11 to 12 at Quinlan Community Center. The annual 13-hour hackathon is open to teens ages 13 to 18 and is organized by the city's Youth Activity Board, Teen Commission, and Recreation Department.</p>

          <p>This year's challenge asked participants to build software focused on health and wellness. The event has been running since 2017&mdash;making it one of the longest-running municipally organized teen hackathons in the South Bay.</p>

          <p>There's something genuinely great about a city parks department running a hackathon. Not every community center doubles as a startup incubator at midnight, but in Cupertino, that's apparently just what happens in April.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://www.cupertino.gov/Parks-Recreation/Events/Hack-Cupertino" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City of Cupertino event page</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ── 9. PG&E Downtown Los Gatos ──
           Source: Town of Los Gatos news flash (losgatosca.gov) -->
      <article class="news-article">
        <div class="news-article-category">Infrastructure &middot; Los Gatos</div>
        <h3 class="news-article-headline">PG&amp;E Is Replacing a Power Pole on Main Street Tonight</h3>
        <p class="news-article-deck">Overnight work at 25 W. Main and Park Avenue. If you're downtown after 9 p.m., expect detours.</p>
        <div class="news-article-byline">April 15, 2026</div>
        <div class="news-article-body">
          <p>PG&amp;E is replacing a power pole overnight from 9 p.m. tonight (Wednesday, April 15) to 6 a.m. Thursday at 25 W. Main Street and Park Avenue in downtown Los Gatos.</p>

          <p>The work will involve temporary road closures and detours in one of the town's most-walked intersections. Residents and businesses in the immediate area should expect noise and light disruptions through the early morning hours.</p>

          <p>Separately, the Town will accept electronic bids for its 2026 Annual Street Repair and Resurfacing Project by 2 p.m. today&mdash;a reminder that beneath the charm of Los Gatos's downtown, there's a municipal government quietly keeping the roads from falling apart.</p>

          <div class="news-source">
            Source: <a href="https://www.losgatosca.gov/m/newsflash" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Town of Los Gatos news flash</a>.
